docs.abstract: After painting a portrait of Taylor, whose killing by police helped galvanize national protests, the artist decided she wanted the work to live on in public.
docs.snippet: After painting a portrait of Taylor, whose killing by police helped galvanize national protests, the artist decided she wanted the work to live on in public.
docs.lead_paragraph: Typically, Amy Sherald’s gallery would handle the sale of her artwork to a collector or an institution. But when it came to her portrait of Breonna Taylor — the 26-year-old medical worker who was shot and killed by police officers in Louisville, Ky. — Sherald herself wanted to see that particular painting all the way home.

headline.main: Amy Sherald Directs Her Breonna Taylor Painting Toward Justice

docs.abstract: MINNEAPOLIS — A third-degree murder charge may be back on the table for Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer charged in the death of George Floyd, after a ruling from the Minnesota Supreme Court on Wednesday.
docs.lead_paragraph: MINNEAPOLIS — A third-degree murder charge may be back on the table for Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer charged in the death of George Floyd, after a ruling from the Minnesota Supreme Court on Wednesday.

headline.main: What happened on the second day of jury selection at the Derek Chauvin trial?

docs.abstract: The governor supports a bill passed on Wednesday that repeals language allowing people to arrest someone who they witnessed committing a crime.
docs.snippet: The governor supports a bill passed on Wednesday that repeals language allowing people to arrest someone who they witnessed committing a crime.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — Georgia lawmakers on Wednesday approved a bill gutting a Civil War-era law that allowed residents to arrest one another, a move championed by critics who said such laws have historically been used by white citizens to justify the killing of African-Americans.

headline.main: Georgia to Weaken Citizen’s Arrest Law Cited in Ahmaud Arbery’s Death
headline.print_headline: Lawmakers in Georgia Curb Civil War-Era Law Allowing Citizen’s Arrests

docs.abstract: A year after nationwide protests against police brutality, the City Council passed a bill limiting qualified immunity, a longstanding legal protection officers had against lawsuits.
docs.snippet: A year after nationwide protests against police brutality, the City Council passed a bill limiting qualified immunity, a longstanding legal protection officers had against lawsuits.
docs.lead_paragraph: A year after nationwide protests against police brutality ignited calls for reform, the New York City Council passed legislation on Thursday aimed at reining in police misconduct by making it far easier to sue officers for conducting illegal searches or using excessive force.

headline.main: It May Soon Be Easier to Sue the N.Y.P.D. for Misconduct
headline.print_headline: City Passes Police Reform,  Making It Easier to Sue For Excessive or Illegal Acts

byline.original: By Jeffery C. Mays and Ashley Southall

docs.abstract: The task of assembling a suitably impartial jury is expected to be one of the most challenging aspects of a case that has generated enormous attention in Minneapolis and around the world.
docs.snippet: The task of assembling a suitably impartial jury is expected to be one of the most challenging aspects of a case that has generated enormous attention in Minneapolis and around the world.
docs.lead_paragraph: Late last year, prospective jurors in Minneapolis and surrounding communities received an extensive questionnaire about their knowledge of the case of Derek Chauvin, the former police officer who is accused of murdering George Floyd. It was a first step to gauge public sentiment about the case and weed out prospective jurors who have strong enough opinions to disqualify them from hearing the case.

headline.main: How will the jury be chosen?

docs.abstract: Protests against police brutality brought the nation’s attention to the Feminist Coalition. Now its members want to change life for Nigerian women.
docs.snippet: Protests against police brutality brought the nation’s attention to the Feminist Coalition. Now its members want to change life for Nigerian women.
docs.lead_paragraph: LAGOS, Nigeria — During the biggest demonstrations in Nigeria’s recent history, 13 women came together to support their fellow citizens risking their lives to march against police brutality.

headline.main: In Nigeria, ‘Feminist’ Was a Common Insult. Then Came the Feminist Coalition.
headline.print_headline: In Nigeria, Women’s Rights Activists Turn an Insult Into a Rallying Cry

docs.abstract: A witness broke down in sobs as he recounted his memory of George Floyd’s arrest. Jurors watched the fatal incident from the perspective of the police officers’ body cameras.
docs.snippet: A witness broke down in sobs as he recounted his memory of George Floyd’s arrest. Jurors watched the fatal incident from the perspective of the police officers’ body cameras.
docs.lead_paragraph: The grief and guilt of witnesses have been center stage throughout the first three days of the trial of Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer accused of killing George Floyd. On Wednesday, the judge temporarily halted the proceedings after a 61-year-old witness broke down in sobs as he recounted his memory of Mr. Floyd’s arrest.

headline.main: Takeaways from the third day of the Derek Chauvin trial.
